–1263","1128–1169":"1128–1169","–1169":"–1169","about 1150":"about 1150","Aft 1234":"after 1234","1164":"1164","1263":"1263","1162":"1162","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","after 1209":"after 1209","1155":"1155","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Scotland":"Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland","Tweedsmuir, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Tweedsmuir, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebleshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Touch-Fraser, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Touch, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fraser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frayser","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasure","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazer","meanings":["Variant of   Fraser  , associated chiefly with northern Ireland."]},{"name":"Fraizer","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frashier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Fraiser","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frizzell","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Old French <i>fresel</i>, <i>frisel</i> ‘lace, ribbon, braid, brooch, frill, ruff’, for someone with an ornate style of dress, or ‘object of little value’ (a diminutive of <i>frese</i>, of ancient Germanic origin).","Scottish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, an alternative form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazier","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."]},{"name":"Frasher","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Fratzscher</b> (see   Frutchey  )."]}]},{"name":"Bernard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was the name of three famous medieval churchmen:  St Bernard  of Menthon (  923–1008 ), founder of a hospice on each of the Alpine passes named after him; the monastic reformer  St Bernard  of Clairvaux (  1090–1153 ); and the scholastic philosopher  Bernard  of Chartres. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. A native Old English form, <i>Beornheard</i>, was superseded by the Norman form."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Bernard Fraser was born in 1164, in Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland as the son of Udard Fraser and Margaret Verch Kylvert. He had at least 1 son with Mary Ogilvie. In 1234, at the age of 70, his occupation is listed as sheriff of tweeddale. He died in 1258, in Tweedsmuir, Peeblesshire, Scotland, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1164–1258":"1164–1258","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1155–1191":"1155–1191","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1172–1209":"1172–1209","1208–1263":"1208–1263","1128–1169":"1128–1169","–1169":"–1169","about 1150":"umbes 1150","Aft 1234":"pärast 1234","1164":"1164","1263":"1263","1162":"1162","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","after 1209":"pärast 1209","1155":"1155","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Scotland":"Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire, Scotland","Tweedsmuir, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Tweedsmuir, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebleshire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Touch-Fraser, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Touch, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1164–1258":"1164–1258","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1155–1191":"1155–1191","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1172–1209":"1172–1209","1208–1263":"1208–1263","1128–1169":"1128–1169","–1169":"–1169","about 1150":"noin 1150","Aft 1234":"1234 jälkeen","1164":"1164","1263":"1263","1162":"1162","1172":"1172","1150":"1150","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","after 1209":"1209 jälkeen","1155":"1155","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Scotland":"Scotland","Drumelzier, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Drumelzier, Peeblesshire, Scotland","Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfarshire